From: VyOS LS1046A Build <build@vyos.io>
Subject: [PATCH] net: phy: swphy: support 10G/5G/2.5G speeds in fixed-link

The NXP SDK DPAA fsl_mac driver does not use the mainline phylink/SFP
framework. When a 10G MAC has no phy-handle and no managed/sfp DTS
properties, the driver falls back to of_phy_register_fixed_link() which
creates a software PHY via fixed_phy_register().

However, swphy_decode_speed() only handles 10/100/1000 and returns
-EINVAL for higher speeds. This causes fixed_phy_register() to fail
for 10G MACs with fixed-link DTS nodes, resulting in:
  swphy: unknown speed
  fsl_mac: probe of 1af0000.ethernet failed with error -22

MII registers cannot represent speeds above 1G, but the actual link
speed is communicated via fixed_phy_status (the fixed_phy_update()
callback), not MII register reads. Map 10000/5000/2500 to
SWMII_SPEED_1000 so that fixed_phy_register() succeeds and the MAC
driver can use the fixed-link PHY for link management.

This is required for NXP LS1046A SDK kernel builds where the 10G SFP+
MACs (MAC9/MAC10) use fixed-link instead of phylink.

Signed-off-by: VyOS LS1046A Build <build@vyos.io>
---
 drivers/net/phy/swphy.c | 22 ++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c b/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c
index 59f1ba4d49bc..4459df30e2c1 100644
--- a/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c
+++ b/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c
@@ -72,6 +72,20 @@ static int swphy_decode_speed(int speed)
 {
 	switch (speed) {
+	case 10000:
+	case 5000:
+	case 2500:
+		/*
+		 * MII registers cannot represent speeds above 1G, but we
+		 * return SWMII_SPEED_1000 to allow fixed_phy_register() to
+		 * succeed. The actual link speed is communicated via
+		 * fixed_phy_status, not MII register reads. This enables
+		 * SDK DPAA 10G MACs to use fixed-link without swphy_read_reg
+		 * warnings for unrepresentable speeds.
+		 */
+		return SWMII_SPEED_1000;
 	case 1000:
 		return SWMII_SPEED_1000;
 	case 100:
